text:
this one is deep.(trigger warning) it was the first thing i noticed when i opened this photo. that dent you see on the upper part of my thigh isn't cellulite (not that there is anything wrong with cellulite, its perfectly normal) that dent is a constant reminder to run the f^ck away from toxic people/relationships. don't be dumb like me and accept their pathetic attempt of an apology to ease away their own guilt. don't make excuses for their behavior, don't blame yourself, don't think things will get better. once domestic violence starts it gets worse and goes down hill fast. i got knocked out cold by the person i loved* the most only to be left alone unconscious. i was sober, he was not. he ran & hid because he was afraid i was going to call the police. if only i could go back in time. when i came to i had to call a taxi(uber wasn't a thing then) to take me to the er. this was once of many occasions. if this helped or touched one person then it was worth telling my true little story that i try and erase from my memory. i have forgave this person, moved on, & we remain courgal because i don't like having negativity in my life. (forgive my horrible grammar or should i say grammer lol)

text:
the difference between angel investing and crowdfunding. the reason why i started to invest and the importance of taking care of yourself. 
i've learned the hard way to be dependant on the next pay check, the stress of not being able to pay the basics. i started working when i was 13 and i've done it all, cleaning houses, waitressing, night club singer and events. when i was 13 i didn't have a r√©sum√©, so i printed 50 copies of a letter and personally handed them out in every caf√©, restaurant and store i could find. the fact that i really really needed a job, meant i was put in a vulnerable position. "fuck off"-money isn't being able to buy an island or a new sports car. it's about being able to walk the fuck away when someone takes advantage of you. several years ago i said i'll never again have a male boss. after #metoo that changed. if something were to happen now i can walk away (financial independence), and i can say something. in this episode of pep talk with @join_pepins we talk about investments, but more importantly - mindset. the episode is in swedish, i hope you like it and share it with someone who needs to know that they can do whatever the f they want in this world. and i'm cursing a lot when i think something is really really important. take the driver's seat of your own life, and don't let anyone hurt you. that's what money is great for, walking away from bad situationsüôåüèΩ

"fuck off"-money is not being able to buy an island or a new sports car. it is about being able to walk the fuck away when someone takes advantage of you. several years ago i said i'll never again have a male boss. after #metoo that changed. if something were to happen now i can walk away (ficial independence), and i can say something. in this episode of pep talk with @join_pepins we talk about investments, but more importantly - mindset. the episode is in swedish, i hope you like it and share it with someone who needs to know that they can do whatever the f they want in this world. and i am cursing a lot when i think something is really really important. take the driver's seat of your own life, and do not let anyone hurt you. that's what money is great for, walking away from bad situationsüôåüèΩ

text:
i just have to put this out there because i read the most heinous things on the internet that i cannot believe, which is probably why i wasn't on social media for a long time. as a survivor of rape, rape culture, and domestic abuse things like the #metoo movement have given women who never had the courage or the platform to be genuinely heard and fought for in a society that slut shames and blames victims for being abused. unfortunately, rape culture has been encouraged and developed by a misogynistic society and women who have made false claims for the come up (which only hurts the women who are really abused and gets the third degree because that one chick who lied). not every man is an abuser/sexist/chauvinist, but not every woman is lying or bitter either. nothing in this world is black and white but everyone is quick to judge a collective based off whatever small sector represents their own thoughts and ideas. i would ask everyone to be mindful of their own macroaggressions and biases because your experiences may have altered your worldview differently than others and everyone is not the same.
.
.
.

text:
a damning report by the guardian last month highlighting the horrifying abuse women are subjected to under the care of medical and nursing staff, when they are going through childbirth. this is already a time of vulnerability and transition, whether one is becoming a new parent or expanding their family with a subsequent pregnancy. women may well feel they are at the mercy of health care staff, hoping they will ensure her safety and dignity, whilst also bringing her child into the world with great care. this article reports how the nature of this abuse is widespread on an international scale. this is not just a healthcare issue occurring in the uk, but a global concern. we have to start questioning why women are silenced, why this power dynamic goes unquestioned and whether this scale of silencing and abuse, rendering women powerless, is rooted in a form of institutional misogyny. sadly what is often found is that women from ethnic minority backgrounds, possibly struggling with language barriers, pay the larger price in the spectrum of best to worst birthing care. or perhaps they can speak english, but they've been raised in a culture where they've learned definitions of femininity and #womanhood mean to behave demure or submissive. they may have been socialised into thinking and believing that it's not appropriate for them to voice their needs/give alternative views, or they should remain submissive to the authority of doctors. this is an example of how gender, culture and race may intersect, all in the context of birthing and motherhood. 
is this second wave of the #metoo movement a much needed step towards change?
#violenceagainstwomen
#birthtrauma
#silencingwomen
#misogyny
#genderculturerace

#genderandrace
#intersectionalityofgendercultureandrace
#metoo2

text:
the body. the #magical, #mystical #machine that allows us to self drive around the #planet. although we #create boxes to put it in to sleep, and conveyor belts to walk on to speed up, and carts to carry it across great distances, it‚Äôs still superior in every way to any #robot ü§ñwe could invent. our bodies are so incredible and yet we tweak them on instagram, feel bad about them, and try to conform them to some standard collective agreement that as children we had no #idea we were buying into. yes, beauty, and beautiful things are always giving us a peaceful feeling, a joy to look at, and a sense of wonder.
üí´
be kind to your #body. it‚Äôs the only #vehicle you have in this life.
üí´‚Äùi never liked to do lingerie as a model,‚Äù says anina net, ‚Äúi didn‚Äôt like the way my ribs stuck out and my hips were big (so i thought). i would break out into a sweat before a shoot measuring myself against the other #models who were measuring themselves against me! i‚Äôm really #lucky that the few catalogs and calendars that i did do had photographers and stylists who made me feel comfortable. they took into consideration my paranoias because they wanted me-anina to be in the photos with my energy. they showed high #professionalism and treated us as models as people, took great care with us. imagine if we could all shed our unconscious bias about bodies? imagine if the world treated women with safety and respect? not exercising power like that of the #metoo movement. because the people i worked with took care of me in these intimate situations, i felt beautiful and comfortable and my inner light shone out. what would the world be like if we could support people to be the best with their flaws and all?‚Äù #greatmanagers #outstanding #powerfulwomen

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
ah, it‚Äôs time for something i‚Äôve been expecting for awhile now which i feel ok about sharing while letting a summer storm soak my skin. 
the rape and abuse i allege i have experienced will not be prosecuted. this is ok!
i think from the start i had a sense of how difficult this kinda stuff is to address in court. it‚Äôs so messy and grey and personal. 
there‚Äôs honestly no desire in me for vengeance or retribution or anything like that, all i want is to get better and be ok.
(while i‚Äôm here i want to publicly note that i never have and never will identify my alleged rapist/abuser so none of my writing should be taken to be about any individual.)
i‚Äôm still going to campaign for victim-survivors of rape and abuse to have better access to justice and to support, because many parts of these systems are broken, but this is informed by all of my experiences with gender-based violence and my resulting personal opinions.

text:
thank you to the lovely people at @allenandunwin for kindly sending me a copy for review.
.
"speak it. write it. read it. make it visible. 
let it be heard.
let courage call to courage everywhere." - jeanette winterson, courage calls to courage everywhere
.
.
adapted from jeanette winterson‚Äôs 2018 richard dimbleby lecture, courage calls to courage everywhere marks one hundred years since women won the right to vote in the uk.
.
winterson looks back over the years, noting how far we have come since 1918 and what still needs to change.
.
courage calls to courage everywhere is very current, touching on the #metoo and time‚Äôs up movements, the women‚Äôs march, trump‚Äôs presidency and artificial intelligence.
.
also included is emmeline pankhurst‚Äôs speech, freedom or death, which i thoroughly enjoyed.
.
i would have preferred the book to have been slightly more cohesive and the historical events structured in a more chronological order; rather than bouncing around from topic to topic and time period to time period, which had the tendency to be disorientating.
.
courage calls to courage everywhere is a great overview of women‚Äôs suffrage and feminism from before 1918 to the present.
.
it's not particularly in depth but it‚Äôs a deeply passionate and a fantastic introduction to feminism, women‚Äôs suffrage and women‚Äôs rights, i highly recommend it to anyone who has an interest in any of these topics.
.
.
.
#couragecallstocourageeverywhere #jeanettewinterson #freedomordeath #emmelinepankhurst #feminism #womenssuffrage #beautifulbooks #bookstagram

.
winterson looks back over the years, noting how far we have come since 1918 and what still needs to change.
.
courage calls to courage everywhere is very current, touching on the #metoo and time‚Äôs up movements, the women‚Äôs march, trump‚Äôs presidency and artificial intelligence.
.
also included is emmeline pankhurst‚Äôs speech, freedom or death, which i thoroughly enjoyed.
.
i would have preferred the book to have been slightly more cohesive and the historical events structured in a more chronological order; rather than bouncing around from topic to topic and time period to time period, which had the tendency to be disorientating.

courage calls to courage everywhere is a great overview of women‚Äôs suffrage and feminism from before 1918 to the present.
.

text:
nabila, 20th, bogor 
jadi sekitar jam 7 malem gue yang kebtulan tinggal di bogor dan kuliah di jakarta dan memutuskan untuk pulang pergi setiap harinya, harus pulang naik kereta yang kebetulan lagi jam rame. karna sangking ramenya gue memutuskan untuk masuk ke gerbong cowok beharap ada mas-mas yang ngasih gue duduk karna berhubung gue cewek, dan karna udah pasti gerbang cewek penuh dan kadang mbak-mbak malah pura-pura tidur biar bisa duduk ga gantian sama yang lain. selama perjalanan gue mulai ngerasa enggak enak karna di perhatiin terus sama bapak-bapak di belakang gue. dan sampe akhirnya si bapak-bapak itu nempelin ‚Äúitunya‚Äù ke belakang gue dan kebetulan kereta itu bentar lagi sampe di stasiun tebet dan gue udah berfikir untuk turun aja karna udah takut banget. pas gue kelur dari kereta bokong gue di colek sama bapak-bapak itu dan sponat gue triak kenceng sampe semua orang liatin gue dan gue bilang ke si bapak ‚Äújangan kurang aja ya lo‚Äù dan satu gerbong itu langsung tertuju ke bapak itu semua, dan sangat terpaksa gue naik kereta selanjutnya
.
.
.

text:
nazhira, 20th, bogor 
jadi kebetulan gue kursus bikin gaun di salah satu tempat di jakarta, karna gue dan temen-temen gue udah kelar kursus itu kita mau ngerayain di salah satu club di daerah scbd. singkat cerita gue lagi di dance floor lagi asik-asik joget sama temen-temen gue tiba-tiba ada cowok ga kenal mepet-mepet, disitu masih gaada rasa apapun gue pikir kaya mau join aja kali. dan tiba-tiba dia joget sambil sengol-sengol dada gue dan gue awalnya minggir-minggir buat menghindahi itu cowok, tapi dia tetep mepet lagi terus gue tanya lo ngapain? terus dia malah sok asik dengan muka mupengnya. akhirnya gue ngadep dia gue tarik mukanya dan gue tonjok idungnya, karna itu bener - bener bikin gue enggak nyaman dan risih .
.
.
.

text:
an old memory with a new truth:

there‚Äôs a part to every story that is still being told. in some cases it is still being written, and in others the story has been lived, yet there‚Äôs little courage to speak it.
.
.
five years ago i had just returned to work since sporadically quitting my former career in higher ed to pursue music (almost two years prior). i was in a great deal of debt and scrambling to pay rent after just making it off of my sister‚Äôs couch from the past several months of having few gigs, no prospects, and dwindling hope in a singing career that i guess wasn‚Äôt meant to be.
.
a temp agency had staffed me with a financial aid job at @moorecollegeart and i was finally starting to see a glimpse of hope resurface.
.
i remember very clearly when this student (referenced in the screenshot of this post) walked in flustered, uneasy, and ashamed, yet desperate to share her truth. in that moment, i hid in the lie that is highlighted above, which depicts me merely sympathetic to her struggle, when i was in fact a mirror of her, but not willing and way too ashamed to say the two words that may have made the difference for us both, #metoo .
.
for months up to this point, i struggled with the pride of my insistent decision to be an artist, unable to pay my bills and properly care for myself, yet too shamed to return home and go back to my 9to5. i turned to a similar lifestyle that began with occasional paid ‚Äúdates‚Äù, then very quickly escalated into more shameful moments, and a life that i would have easily judged on any other woman up until that moment. even after starting this new job, i had become so accustomed to fast money that stopping was not an immediate thought.
.
.
people judge my work with #happilybetterafter and @creativesoncampus and assume this kindness/humility thing just happened. nah. i see so many people, especially students, and am easily able to find myself in them, or glimpses of a version of me that once lived.
.
everyone has a story, even the ‚Äúbad‚Äù guys. like it or not, truth just is.
.
thank you all for providing me this space to share and reach new levels of freedom üíõ
.
.
#happilybetter #everydaybetter

text:
recently, i had a client share her story for the very first time. it was after working together for several months. when we began, she just wasn't ready to go there.
.
.
.
as we worked together, she felt lighter and freer with every session. her husband noticed the differences and even yelled; "thank you!" to me in the background when my client and i were on the phone one day.
.
.
.
the day she was ready to share was chosen by her. why? pushing ourselves to share when we aren't ready can¬†do more harm than good.
the next question you may be asking is; how can she do therapy without telling the story? in the work that i do, the body tells the story through your emotions and your beliefs; the two are one and your body will store your experience differently than anyone else does. .
.
.
you are unique. your experience is unique. shouldn't your inner transformation work be too? .
.
.
if you want a unique experience of healing your history of abuse and your health in the process, call me for a free consultation. set up an appointment at this link https://meghaworth.as.me/free-talk  you‚Äôll gain a life you didn‚Äôt know you could.

text_retweet: while the #metoo movement has created alot of buzz globally, and opened up a space to have essential conversations about gender equality, it is just the tip of the iceberg. the world economic forum 2018 report found that at current rate, the global gender gap across a range of areas will not close for another 108 years, while it is expected to take 202 years to close the workplace gap. today, it's more critical than ever to take active steps to close this gap sooner rather than later. at getupgo! we are playing our role by launching two new programs very close to our heart: gender inclusivity program and women in the workplace. stay tuned! #genderequality #worldeconomicforum #metoo #gendergap #love #instagood #me #follow #followme #tagforlikes #self #like4like #like #instadaily #igers #instalike #follow4follow #bestoftheday #likeforlike #instamood #life #repost #my #cool #followback #instafollow #f4f #l4likeforlikesback

text:
this is a thought thats been heavy on my mind for a few days now and because of that i knew it was something we needed to speak on.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i've been in multiple situations where i've gone on a date or had an in depth conversation with someone and after a certain amount of time they alluded to it being time for them to 'give it up.' i vividly remember one specific situation that broke my heart where i had a long conversation with someone and at the end she said:
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
"so you want me to give you (oral sex)?"
i said "what?"
she said "that's normally how it goes. a guy listens to my problems then i have to pay them back with sex."
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
she said that so matter of fact. it was on that moment i understood the 'all men are dogs' idea. to her, they were. that was her experience. and in that moment i felt extreme guilt for my manhood and at the same time grace that i was able to at least be one person that broke the pattern.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
there is obviously much conversation to be had around this and i have much i want to say but i'll end with this. ‚¨áÔ∏è
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
women take notice: a date does not equal sex. dinner does not equal sex. attention does not equal sex. conversation does not equal sex. nothing equals sex except you both wanting it.

text: looking back at some past accomplishments, this was a big one for me. it's all hand-stitched... #metoo stitching over and over in nearly 30 different languages from around the world. the negative space created spells: time's up.  this art quilt was accepted into a national juried show and was awarded second place in the category of embroidery / handwork. :) #focusonfibrearts *** i still have this art quilt and i'm not sure what to do with it. if you hear of any exhibitions looking for feminist art, please let me know. it's not right for this to be hiding in my studio. i would like it to be out and be seen.

text:
life is a beautiful journey if we don‚Äôt allow the brokenness to define us!
.
savor that thought for a moment.
.
life has not been easy for either of us, casey jokes that it‚Äôs been even harder since he met me, but he‚Äôs probably not wrong.
.
neither of us had a picture book childhood, his stories are not mine to share, but if you‚Äôve been around long enough or read back far enough you know several of the mountains that have been placed in front of me.
.
i had selfish and addicted parents so my grandparents chose to raise me. weekends with dad and memories of police and yelling and ... and then i grew into the lifestyle i once loathed. addiction, promiscuity, hard knock. when i discovered i was pregnant at 14 years young it rerouted my course. i had someone dependent on my decisions so i decided they better be good ones. abuse, sexual abuse, mental abuse, verbal abuse. officers and court dates, brokenness, abandonment, and then i met casey. life before him was hard but we‚Äôve not exactly had a walk through the park either. financially insecure, infertility, custody, lawyers and papers and court and persecution for trying to do what was right, crying and praying for a way ... adoption and death, longing and hoping and harsh words. new beginnings and new opportunities. miscarriage. and waiting ...
.
every struggle had the opportunity to define me. to define us. every trial had the power to leave me the victim but i chose to fight to become someone worth knowing. i fought for this life and i refuse to not acknowledge its beauty.

text:
i‚Äôm close to finishing this memoir, and let me tell you...it‚Äôs like chewing on some amazing beef jerky. it is incredible, yet hard to read. why? because it goes through the rape of alice sebold when she was 19, in college, and a virgin. you have to take it in doses because you hurt as you read it. it is devastatingly beautiful. thus far, it has made me feel validated in my own experiences with sexual abuse, and the anger and rage you hold within you when you have been violated. the complete aggression you feel but are told to stifle because you are a woman and are supposed to be sugar and spice. instead, you have a flame in you and want to set a fire that will obliterate an entire landscape. eventually, the fire becomes ice that takes a long damn time to thaw out. this is reality. this is life.

what are you trying to avoid is becoming a self-fulfilling prophecy unfolding at a steady pace, with full moon on 19 april highlights the need for adjustment in listening to & dealing with others to come to impartial decisions. and the full moon on 19th may will shake up the old structures of any transformation that hasn‚Äôt started yet. the period between 1-16th june will be the picture-perfect snapshot that not everything can be controlled.

text:
i‚Äôm back from my impromptu social media hiatus after taking some time off to address my mental health.
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôve always known that healing isn‚Äôt linear- and i know i say it here all the time. but what i‚Äôve recently discovered (via therapy) is my subconscious mindset that i need to be a better version of myself in order to be *ready* to heal. think of it like feeling the need to lose a little bit of weight before you can show your face at the gym again and get in your best shape. now apply that concept to mental wellness. i‚Äôve felt like i haven‚Äôt deserved to heal yet because i‚Äôm not good enough to heal yet. i know- that sounds ridiculous. but i‚Äôve gotten so used to trauma and anxiety and depression that i‚Äôve also gotten used to the idea that its all i deserve. i can spout all the positive affirmations i want and journal until the cows come home, but i‚Äôm ready to admit that none of it will work unless i‚Äôm able to turn off the part of my brain that doesn‚Äôt think i deserve it. ‚Ä¢
healing isn‚Äôt linear. i‚Äôm not saying that i‚Äôve never made progress. i‚Äôm not saying that my entire journey up to now has been for naught. i‚Äôm saying that this is where i am right now. and i‚Äôm glad that this realization is finally out in the open. ‚ú®üå± #selflove #love #survivor #survivoradvocate #survivorselfcare #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen #rapesurvivor #csasurvivor #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalwellness #therapy #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #metoomovement #generalizedanxietydisorder #cptsd #depression #highfunctioningdepression #highfunctioninganxiety

dear survivor, 
you did nothing wrong. you did nothing to bring harm to yourself. you never put yourself in any situation. you should never be forced to disclose, you should never feel bad about disclosing. you deserve to be heard, valued and respected. although sometimes the media and the people around us may express certain views or opinions - those do not represent you or what you have gone through. anbu is here to serve you, however you wish to be supported.

text:
i love a good ad. in fact, if it were up to me i would have the cheaper hulu version with no ads, but my husband hates them so i have to get my commercial fix through websites like @adweek and @advertisingweek.
.
the #gillette ad from a few weeks ago, along with the backlash of (some) guys saying ‚Äúdon‚Äôt tell me what to do‚Äù made me cry from hope while watching... and cry from anger and shock while hearing some of the backlash from people that didn‚Äôt understand that it‚Äôs a pretty simple concept.
.

i have a son who we are trying to raise as a good human being. as a guy who will stand up to others when they are being bullies or toxic.
.
like i said, it‚Äôs pretty simple ‚Äì when you see someone picking on someone else - say something. hold others accountable. because right now we live in a world where some bad people are in charge. and we have to hold them accountable. üëä

text:
okay insta followers, i think it‚Äôs time that i am honest with you. 
#bellletstalk is something that hits home with me.
someone who suffers from ptsd, depression and anxiety.
after 4 suicide attempts in two months, a brutal sexual assault and multiple relapses, 49 days, 1176 hours in the hospital. 
tomorrow is a day or a chance to talk about something that isn‚Äôt often talked about or talked about enough. 
after i was sexually assaulted i suffered with thoughts of suicide often having to be talked down from it. in december i swallowed over 70 different medications, 13 different pill bottles due to this constant struggle. 
but with suicide, you‚Äôre not ending the pain, you‚Äôre giving it too someone else. 
i stayed in a psych ward most of the time crisis where it‚Äôs a padded room, no access to the light, no furniture just a mattress and non rip blankets. 
after that i was brought to the wards itself where i was free to walk around the hospital. 
i am one of the lucky ones, ones who her family found her just in time or friends called 911. 
i am speaking out to raise this awareness. 
so here is the real me, after months of torture on my body, self blaming. 
please tweet, text, post, anything you can to #bellletstalk tomorrow because despite what i have been though, i am stronger because of it and so many other people.
speak up, tell your story & most importantly reach out to those who are isolated. 
you are not alone. #metoo #bellletstalk

text:
ironman chattanooga training
.
day 2 of my 10-week beginner half marathon training plan. i‚Äôve been getting asked which one i‚Äôm using and it‚Äôs this one:
.
this ten-week plan from soar running coach ben noad will take you from the couch to 21.1km via a very gradual build up in your training that will help you avoid getting injured. there are four sessions a week on the plan, but many of these will be short, or a mix of running and walking.
.
i found this online and i love how gradual it is. i‚Äôm just gaining back my running physical and more importantly mental fitness. today was day 2: 15 mins consecutively. i did a big incline build to 3% held it and went back down in that time. it helped to vary it up and break it down to ‚Äúminute increments‚Äù which is like mini goals for me üòÇüôåüèΩ i felt strong. i felt like i probably could have gone longer but what‚Äôs important to me the next month is finding consistency and finishing each and every run feeling empowered and confident. whether i physically can do more is irrelevant to me now as i build my mental running fitness. üí™üèΩüî•üôåüèΩ
.
anyways, if you‚Äôre looking for a 1/2 marathon program that starts super gradual, so far i like it and how it‚Äôs laid out so search it up and join me üòçüôåüèΩ
.
also...very oddly i‚Äôve liked running in the evenings lately üò≥üò≥üò≥ it clears my mind i feel like it releases any tension from  the day! now i‚Äôm not getting all excited because it‚Äôs been 2 days and it‚Äôs much harder to get motivation but let‚Äôs see if it sticks! hahaha!
.
are you an am or pm runner?!?
.

text:
i deserved peace. i deserved justice. i deserved healing. we all did. we all do. but we live in a world that doesn‚Äôt support that belief. each day, we absorb your insensitive, biased, uneducated, malicious thoughts and opinions regarding sexual assault. this month, women all over the world (many you absolutely know personally) read, heard, and absorbed your thoughts and opinions on r. kelly and the surviving r. kelly documentary. we saw your memes. we saw your ‚Äúseparate the art from the artist‚Äù posts. all while wishing we could separate ourselves from the assault. wishing we could stop hearing the ‚Äúbelt buckle hit the floor‚Äù. last year, we listened to you crucify christine basely ford for when she came forward. and the year before, your daughter heard you vilify the ‚Äúwilling whores‚Äù that took too long to come forward in the cosby case.

you don‚Äôt get to complain about the timeline in which women come forward while you do everything you can to keep us in hiding.

before you chastise women on their timing, take personal responsibility for the toxic space you‚Äôve helped create for victims. [excerpt #2 from the belt buckle] when i wrote this article, i first had all the beautiful and brave women and men that shared their stories in mind. i wanted to share their truth in a way that honors them and ignites their healing. but i also had the misguided in mind.

if you defended r. kelly or cosby or had insensitive, rash words regarding the kavanaugh case - it's not too late to do better. i planned to write this well thought out call to action for you all. but... like no... do better.

follow the link in my bio if you are ready to do better or are even questioning some of your past behavior. i hope you are enlightened. and if not... at least stop talking. talk less. yes... talk less!

thank you in advance! xo
.
.
.
#muterkelly #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #timesupnow

text:
who gets to be beautiful?¬†and who gets to be ugly?¬†the answer isn‚Äôt simple.¬†when we talk about beauty, we often lack the necessary nuance. we tend to deal in romantic myths of beauty, but reality is ugly: beauty is not in the eye of the beholder.¬†beauty does not come from within.

only some of us get to be beautiful; being beautiful is a privilege. indeed, whether or not you get are accepted into the beautiful club has an effect on your income, access to healthcare, and susceptibility to violence.¬†it even has an effect on whether you live or die.¬†‚Äúbeautiful,‚Äù an adjective, is defined as proximity to cis white womanhood. 
beautiful means light skin, it means light eyes, it means pale skin, a thin body, and a feminine frame. beauty is a litmus test for white supremacy: the closer your ability to pass as white, the better your chance of being deemed beautiful, and the further your chances from being killed.

beauty, as a construct, has been defined by feminists as a tool of the patriarchy. a trick, if you will, to get women to conform so that men find them desirable and worthy of love. in this view, to feed into beauty is to feed into patriarchy. but what does it mean to ignore ‚Äúbeauty‚Äù? what does it mean to rebel against it? what does that even look like? for women of color, it too often means putting oneself in harm‚Äôs way. this is not an ask i am willing to make of my sisters.

too many of our discussions around beauty politics and beauty myths consist of cis white women opining on how sick they are of men reducing them to their outer appearances. but beauty is a far more complex structure that requires deeper analysis. the impact of being deemed beautiful to society means hurt feelings to some people and broken bones to others. social media has provided a space where women of color, gender non-conforming people, trans women, women of varying abilities and sexualities, queer women, and more can feel relative safety in owning their appearance in a world that wants us dead.

if that is not revolution, i do not know what is.

text:

other rapists and sexual abusers are often famous people, whom also have a lot of money, but also have the public behind them. people will side with a celebrity over a general citizen because they idolise them, and can‚Äôt imagine their favourite singer/actor etc committing such atrocities. so they accuse the victims of falsely accusing these celebrities, pinning on them that they ‚Äújust want to bring down their careers‚Äù.
people who rape/sexually assault and/harass others, need to lose their jobs immediately and be forbidden to be in such positions of power again. raping or sexually assaulting another human being, causes trauma that the victim will have with them for the rest of their lives. it‚Äôs not something that should be punished with a slap on the wrist. it‚Äôs a complete violation of someone‚Äôs body. actors, singers, priests, police officers, doctors, and people working in the government should have their title stripped from them, and be locked away too.
in saying that, men who aren‚Äôt even in positions such as these, are barely ever convicted for their crime against these women.
it‚Äôs a really disgusting world that we live in, and this is why #metoo and feminism exist. and they will not go away until all of these disgusting social issues are fixed.

text:
this is such an important topic:
how can we expect for the divine masculine to arise, if it is not whole inside us in the first place?

so much is transpiring in the world. by now many may have heard of the #metoo movement, the sexually taking advantage  in the name of 'healing' and spirituality like the recent uncover of john of god in brazil. 
regardless of gender and sexual orientation, we all have masculine and feminine energies within us.

it is probably safe  to  say that almost nobody in the entire world has experienced being continuously held in the awakened loving presence of the divine masculine.

most likely all of us have experienced the wounded divine masculine in some shape or from:
by being bullied, stepped on to, controlled or dominated, sexually abused or objectified, inappropriately touched or talked to. or the complete absence of a safe awakened divine masculine love and embrace.

every baby born in this world is born into a world where there is war and suffering. remember, in the energetic aspects we  are not separate from one another.

we still have differences in salary for the same job done by men and women.

there has been a focus of bringing forth the energies of the divine feminine*, hoping that the divine masculine automatically would come forth, step up and just heal itself, popping up like mushrooms after a good rain, whole and complete. *(some have been confused by using seduction, female sexyness and the goddess movement by getting what they want, which is just another form of control and manipulation.)
one thing that very human being has, is the power over our own energies, and thus to fully embrace the divine masculine and divine feminine energies within.

each single person  can  change the world by fully healing their divine masculine within.
yes, imagine if we all do this, it will change the world! 
what we change inside will come forth on the outside.
and what you have on the inside nobody can take away from you. 
to  read more click below:
https://www.odiledellaquila.com/teleseminar2019 #awakening #divinemasculine #divinemasculineawakening #healingthedivinemasculine #embodyingwholeness #beyondhealing

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
3/7
i moved to florida thinking my marriage was over. i didn‚Äôt know what the future would hold.
i needed a place to rest, i needed to be cared for and i needed space to heal.
.
i had begun to research ways to heal myself naturally. i never heard of someone ever healing themselves of hypothyroidism so i took to the magic interwebs to find out if this was possible by researching mostly via the mighty google machine. ü§ì
.
i found out so much information about how everything in the body is connected and i found stories of people who had cured their hypothyroidism through nutrition and rest.
i began researching women‚Äôs issues and women‚Äôs hormones‚Äîi learned so much!
i found lots of books and now a few of them are staples in my house. especially:
-the period repair manual
-woman code
i want to recommend these right away to all the women in my life, if you haven‚Äôt read them‚Äîget them!!
.
i was determined to heal myself naturally as i believed it wasn‚Äôt my destiny in life to live with everything i had been diagnosed with. i came to the conclusion through all of my research that i had basically caused my body to shut down because of stress and trauma.
.
i learned how trauma, stress & anxiety affected your hormones and glands and i became a talking hormone encyclopedia for a while.
.
when i moved to florida i continued to research and tried to stick to my natural lifestyle i had developed years before and intended to be more loving towards myself in my eating habits and consumption of personal products.
.
((continued in following post.))
.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
the first painting is called "roy" and is a portrait of roy lichtenstein by chuck close. chuck close is also one of my most favourite artists, but these days that is tinged with sadness. chuck was accused of sexual harassment and inappropriate behavior during the beginnings of the #metoo movement. like many artists, he is egotistical due to his (much deserved) success and all but admitted to the claims, refusing to apologize or take any care of them. in short, he's an asshole. but his work (especially as a printmaker) has always been close to my heart and i now refer to him as "the artist i'm not supposed to like". but i love his work. i'm awed by it. he is brilliant. a designer who has conquered the paintbrush.

the first painting is called "roy" and is a portrait of roy lichtenstein by chuck close. chuck close is also one of my most favourite artists, but these days that is tinged with sadness. chuck was accused of sexual harassment and inappropriate behavior during the beginnings of the #metoo movement. like many artists, he is egotistical due to his (much deserved) success and all but admitted to the claims, refusing to apologize or take any care of them. in short, he's an asshole. but his work (especially as a printmaker) has always been close to my heart and i now refer to him as "the artist i am not supposed to like". but i love his work. i am awed by it. he is brilliant. a designer who has conquered the paintbrush.

text:
meet the creators of hook up- julie tepperman and chris thornborrow!! i remember when i first auditioned for julie and chris at the tapestry opera general auditons. when they invited me to the callbacks and told me what the piece was about, i knew that i really wanted to be a part of this show. the #metoo movement had just begun and was something that i wanted to engage in, but didn‚Äôt know how. ‚Äúhook up‚Äù has allowed me the opportunity to examine these topics through theatre and share it with the community. 
i‚Äôve had conversations with both male and female friends regarding consent, and it‚Äôs concerning to see how so many people seem to not understand or have different ideas of what consent means. 
only 1 in 3 canadians understand what sexual assault means.

in 82% of sexual assaults the perpetrator is known to the victim.

most perpetrators don‚Äôt consider themselves perpetrators.

when i was growing up, sexual assault and consent weren‚Äôt discussed a lot, either at home or in school. my hope is that this beautiful show that julie tepperman (librettist) and chris thornborrow (composer) created, which targets younger audiences, will be a way in which young people can engage in the conversation and bring awareness to these issues. 
@aliciaault #takeover #theatre #opera #musicaltheatre #beyondwallstpm #tapestryopera #shedoesthecity #metoo #hookupto #acting #singing

meet the creators of hook up- julie tepperman and chris thornborrow!! i remember when i first auditioned for julie and chris at the tapestry opera general auditons. when they invited me to the callbacks and told me what the piece was about, i knew that i really wanted to be a part of this show. the #metoo movement had just begun and was something that i wanted to engage in, but didn‚Äôt know how. ‚Äúhook up‚Äù has allowed me the opportunity to examine these topics through theatre and share it with the community. 
i‚Äôve had conversations with both male and female friends regarding consent, and it‚Äôs concerning to see how so many people seem to not understand or have different ideas of what consent means. 
only 1 in 3 canadians understand what sexual assault means.

in 82% of sexual assaults the perpetrator is known to the victim.

most perpetrators don‚Äôt consider themselves perpetrators.

when i was growing up, sexual assault and consent weren‚Äôt discussed a lot, either at home or in school. my hope is that this beautiful show that julie tepperman (librettist) and chris thornborrow (composer) created, which targets younger audiences, will be a way in which young people can engage in the conversation and bring awareness to these issues. 
@aliciaault #takeover #theatre #opera #musicaltheatre #beyondwallstpm #tapestryopera #shedoesthecity #metoo #hookupto #acting #singing

text:
as i have presented different scenarios and questions to black men. the one thing that has become very clear is the black men feel we have no voice and no one wants to hear our pain. now with this whole #metoo movement and women being heard as they should. @terrycrews was brave enough to do something many men before him didn‚Äôt do. he spoke on his own sexual assault. since then he spoke on how many men have attacked him for speaking out or for accusing him of even allowing it to happen. now as we all know the black community has so much trauma they do not know how to deal with. @realdlhughley had an interview and spoke on his views on what happened to #terrycrews. now as many people do he said  if it was me i would beat his ass. which we hear every time an attack happens to a black person from someone. when that is not what happens in real life when those same people are put in the same situation. i always tell people it is easy to say what you would do from the outside. every day we see black people brave enough to attack their own. yet they don‚Äôt have the same strength as white people. black people suffer from a trauma where we do not feel we can fight back against white people even when we are in the right. we also know that our lives do not matter so fighting our own is easy. so all i want is people to think of the double standard of how our black men are treated compared to the rest. terry crew is just one of billions of men who have said nothing about the trauma they have endured because of fear of being mad a joke. think about that for a second. i respect #dlhughley but this is one time i think you are wrong sir --------------------------------------------------

text:
i honestly thought when i quit smoking, it would be the end of me getting sick all the time, but apparently #marathontraining tears my immune system down tooü§í... but this isn't the purpose of my post, i digress...
.
why do we, as #women , spend so much time and energy tearing each other down? we should be lifting each other up!üë≠
.
when i think back to my 1st 5k in 2013, i was so excited to have finished, in a respectable 27 min for my first event mind you! and after years of being told "you can't ", "you won't ", and my personal favorite "you'll just quit anyway." this was a big deal to me!üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
know what i remember most? a girl that night, while out, hearing that i ran...i was talking about it, obviously, it was a huge accomplishment for me. she said "that's not even that fast."üòï like, wow, thanks for that. .
.
fast forward to 6 months ago, i was getting a haircut, about to #run #mcm. the girl cutting my hair, (not my usual girl btw, she is super supportive) upon hearing my goal of getting a #bq, said "my boyfriend did it on his first try" and "it is not even that hard." she was aware this was my 6th attempt. she herself not a #runner. mind blown. didn't even know how to respond. ü§ê
.
where's the encouragement? where's the "you got this girl ?" idk if it's misplaced jealousy or women projecting their own fears, insecurities, and inadequacies onto each other but we need to stop! üõë
.
we can do better than this ladies, with the #metoo movement happening and #feminism on the rise, i know it's possible! and while we're at it, maybe we need to stop pointing our fingers at and blaming men for holding us back, and take a good long look in the mirror....i think we're doing a pretty good job at that ourselves. üôÖ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
if you've made it this far, thanks for 'listening ', rant over. bye.üëã

text:
fear has been on my mind a lot lately. 
hear me out.

fear kept me from pursuing my dreams in 2018. fear that people wouldn't like my work. fear that i would fail. fear that wouldn't/couldn't deliver the beautiful and amazing photographs i saw all over social media.

but then something clicked, and i realized i had to stop looking outward for approval. you see, it wasn't until 2017 that i started to recognize this issue. 
i, like so so so many, am a survivor of childhood sexual abuse. one thing you lose after experiencing that is your voice. i had learned that my voice didn't matter bc he was the adult so his voice was the only voice. my voice didn't matter. period. and i lost sight of it. i lived my life in a way to make others like me. and if they didn't, i felt like my world was crashing. i looked outside myself for everything i did.

y'all. it took me 14 years to realize this! 14!!! the same age i was when it all happened! 
here's the thing, healing will come when you're ready. when you're in a safe place. when you feel safe. 
so, this year i am claiming my voice asking myself things like 
instead of, "what if people don't like it? they'll know i'm a failure." (but honestly, would they? i highly doubt it.)
i would ask myself, "how do i feel about this photo?" instead of focusing on all the things i didn't wrong during a photo session, i will ask myself, "how do i feel that session went? how can i improve?" but also, "what went well?" and admire the art i helped make. 
i started listening to myself more, that instinct, that intuition. and i love it! 
y'all, i am so excited to carry this into every area of life, but especially my work! 
tell me, friends, what's been holding you back from pursuing your dreams, your happiness, or your healing?

text:
something about snow quiets the mind and calms the heart. just as snow makes things beautiful and bright, jesus and his love makes all things beautiful and bright too. even things we feel could never be beautiful again, things we are ashamed of or embarrassed to talk about. whether it be your #metoo story or #suicideloss or #postpartumdepression or your #eatingdisorderrecovery... i've been through all of these things, and others. we all have struggles, so never ever ever be ashamed of your story. your story makes you strong. your story gives hope to others. your story makes you... you! and even if you feel certain parts are still hard and not as beautiful as you want, share anyway. you will get there. that snow will come and make things bright and beautiful again. sooner than you think. so never lose hope, never give up, keep going... one step at a time, even if you take some steps backwards in the process (we all do) fight for your beautiful!!! .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
the me too movement, where do i start. this movement is very near and dear to my heart. and it‚Äôs helped a lot of people. 
what a lot of people don‚Äôt know is this movement has actually been around since 2006. it was created by tarana burke. it started to be a well known hashtag back in 2017 when alyssa milano tweeted a tweet saying to say #metoo if you have been sexually harassed or assaulted. hundreds upon hundreds of people started posting and saying #metoo. there have been many women who have come out and said what happened to them. and some of the men who did this to them were famous. imagine having to come out about what happened to you. and now imagine having to do that in front of millions of people. so many people get so much hate and people saying ‚Äúi don‚Äôt believe you!‚Äù ‚Äúyou‚Äôre lying!‚Äù just for telling the truth. we have to believe people who tell us their stories. and to all the people who don‚Äôt believe them, ask yourselves why? why don‚Äôt you believe them? why would anyone make that up? why would they put them selves through that torment? just why?

text:
rossen‚Äôs #owv2019goals üíñ ‚Äúif you wouldn‚Äôt say it to someone you love, don‚Äôt say it yourself‚Äô is a statement i‚Äôm trying to follow this 2019. however, there are many many many times where i feel like i definitely miss the prerequisite for that. self-love is a hard thing that seems to be more like a never-ending pursuit, yet i have always found myself able to pour out my affections to all my friends. in the midst of one of my depressive spirals, i kept repeating to myself a mantra of how disgusting and repulsive i was. somehow this led me to take a step back and  think about all the complaints my friends have had about their looks, behaviours, or habits that i couldn‚Äôt even believe. these things that i either never noticed or would never change about them were issues for them. if i adored them so entirely despite whatever insecurities they brought up, then maybe i could frame my mindset like that for my own problems too. how would i console them if they said that to me? it‚Äôs difficult when you‚Äôre stuck in your head 24/7 but i‚Äôm sure with repetition you might even trick yourself into actually believing it. 
above all, just do your best and forgive the rest.‚Äù ‚Äî @confident.liar #ourwomensvoices ‚ù§Ô∏è

text: snow day #art. kids have been creating since they got off the bus and i‚Äôm all ‚Äúmake some art? yes please, #metoo !‚Äù so, i started in the center with a hexagon, and i‚Äôm all, ‚Äúwhy a hexagon?‚Äù and then, as i was led by my intuition from the center outwards, i realized, ‚Äúof course! a #snowflake! six-sided crystals are landing by the millions all around me! hexagonal shapes, all distinct, flying everywhere outside in this moment. no wonder the hexagon is in my consciousness!‚Äù then, the word ‚Äúecstasy‚Äù appeared in my mind. i wrote it down. and then i‚Äôm all, ‚Äúwhy ecstasy?‚Äù and then i realized, ‚Äúbecause i‚Äôm doing what i want! i‚Äôm with my kids, at home, making art, during the day. it‚Äôs a beautiful moment and i feel happy, healthy and fulfilled. which means...ecstasy. thank you life.‚Äù and then, even better, i had been having this vision of living somewhere among the trees, and i kept picturing snow on evergreens right out my window. i looked out and saw my vision fulfilled, and i didn‚Äôt have to go anywhere new. it was right where i was all along...#mandala

text: i always thought that rape culture was "out there" and "all around us". i always thought that the men and women i know would never tolerate someone in our midst if they treated women in vile and illegal ways. i thought that we were all safe together and all the shit people were on the outside. but it's never the case. we all like to think that we are good people and that we would make the right choices in difficult situations. we all like to think that we would never accept or excuse sexual assault, rape, or domestic violence. but when a perpetrator is your friend, the situation feels different. you suddenly have to sacrifice something. it's not just a fantasy scenario where you play hero and stand up for what is right. to do what's right, you have to lose a friend whom you love. you have to shun them and confront them. you have to no longer associate with them. the choice to do what's right suddenly becomes laden with anxiety and sadness and loss. maybe you can help this friend? maybe what you heard about them isn't true? maybe the woman that told you exaggerated? and there you are, trying to find a way not to believe her, or finding a way not to take action. both count - if you believe a woman, you must take action,  or you are shit. if you believe her and do nothing, you are showing that her experience doesn't matter to her - that sexual assault, or rape, or domestic violence, or whatever it is, doesn't matter to you. that her pain doesn't matter to you. if you don't believe her, then you are shit. no woman wants to come and tell you about what happened to her. she's already been living in a society that tells her that she's weak, or should be ashamed, or is to blame. that no one will believe her. that she must have led him on or done something to provoke it. that she is overreacting. so if she tells you, believe her. stand by her. take action. don't let awkwardness or fear of confrontation, or friendship, or your feelings, trump  that your friend did something terrible. don't let it trump her experiences, or her betrayal, or her pain. (continued in comments)

text:
part two of yesterday‚Äôs post. we came across an article about an imam in the uk who admitted to having ‚Äúrelationships‚Äù (i.e. abusing) multiple women. see link in bio. in light of his admission, the board of the mosque met and came up with four conditions. we posted about one condition yesterday and here‚Äôs another:
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
‚Äúhe is to look for a spouse as a priority‚Äù
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶.
no, he really shouldn‚Äôt. and here‚Äôs why.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
perpetrators of sexual violence are using sex and sexuality as the weapon, and power and control as the motive. sexual violence is not about fulfilling ‚Äúsexual urges.‚Äù it‚Äôs about misusing your privilege and power against those who are vulnerable.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
this means that perpetrators are more than likely to use whatever emotional, spiritual, and physically abusive strategies they used against their victims in their marriage against their spouse.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶.
men like this perpetrator need to focus on themselves by seeking therapy, working to change their thoughts and behaviors, reflecting on the harm that they did, looking at restorative justice actions for the survivors, and so much more before they even consider marriage as an option.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
marriage will not change this perpetrator. marriage doesn‚Äôt even change those of us who aren‚Äôt perpetrators. we are who we are before and after marriage.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
and marriage is hard work. life becomes more challenging as two people merge lives. how could someone who abuses power and control to victimize others be a healthy spouse?
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶.
suggestions such as these are not only dangerous from a practical perspective, but an islamic one as well. in the spirit of the prophet, peace be upon him, who would never allow someone who harms others to be married to someone else without first addressing their issues - we need to seriously push back against marriage as a solution to sexual violence.
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..
[image description: a white square image with black text that states perpetrators of sexual violence shouldn‚Äôt get married until they‚Äôve worked on themselves.]
‚Ä¶‚Ä¶..

text:
~yes this can be true @cleowade but i feel statements like these need a ‚Äòwarning label‚Äô
from someone who has navigated speaking up
.
.
it is terrifying to speak up because 
the essence of what happened to you is that you had your power taken away,bringing it up &
talking about it can take you straight out of the now and into the direct felt experience which is deeply triggering 
we need to feel a solid connection with the person we are telling when making this step
to be regulated ,feel grounded and most importantly in control
choose carefully who you open up to because they too can become one more piece of flying debris in an already dangerous storm.
you should really only share with people who have earned the right to hear your story.

this is what i‚Äôve learnt ~ üí´üí´
.
.

text:
honestly , yesterday i had an episode and my depression was really bad , when your healing and also in recovery after being addicted to self-harm for so long it's tough . thing's aren't going to be easy and i know i will have up and downs . yesterday i still got out of bed and went to work , i worked out and i even communicated my feelings to my roommates and best friend instead of shutting myself in and crying . my past will always be just my past, and of course it will never define who i am today or what happens to the present me because im in control of what is happening now . that being said , it doesn't mean my flashbacks or nightmares will disappear forever . i know they will come and go , i follow @r.h.sin because everything he post really speaks to me and reminds me that just because i feel like i've been tainted from my past and no one will ever accept that, doesn't mean that's true. someone or even how my best friend accepts , someone will accept all of that and find the beauty in it that i never could . i just need to keep pushing myself to be better everyday and remind myself how loved i am by those i surround myself with . 
it will be okay , thing's get better day by day and there is always a bright side to the darkness. don't let the darkness control you ‚ù§‚ù§ you got this :) #motivation #inspiration #venezuelan #mentalhealth

honestly , yesterday i had an episode and my depression was really bad , when your healing and also in recovery after being addicted to self-harm for so long it is tough . thing's are not going to be easy and i know i will have up and downs . yesterday i still got out of bed and went to work , i worked out and i even communicated my feelings to my roommates and best friend instead of shutting myself in and crying . my past will always be just my past, and of course it will never define who i am today or what happens to the present me because im in control of what is happening now . that being said , it does not mean my flashbacks or nightmares will disappear forever . i know they will come and go , i follow @r.h.sin because everything he post really speaks to me and reminds me that just because i feel like i have been tainted from my past and no one will ever accept that, does not mean that's true. someone or even how my best friend accepts , someone will accept all of that and find the beauty in it that i never could . i just need to keep pushing myself to be better everyday and remind myself how loved i am by those i surround myself with . 
it will be okay , thing's get better day by day and there is always a bright side to the darkness. do not let the darkness control you ‚ù§‚ù§ you got this :) #motivation #inspiration #venezuelan #mentalhealth

text:
thank you @caelynnmillerkeyes for sharing your story.  this happens way too often.  i hope women who have gone through the same thing find strength when they hear you.

for anyone who missed it, last night caelynn shared a story about being drugged at a party, publicly exposed, and sexually assaulted.  a group witnessed. but most of the perpetrators were never caught/convicted.

this is everyone's responsibility.  staying silent is easy and snitches get stitches.  but wouldn't you rather get a million stitches than let this happen?  wouldn't you rather lose all your friends? 
p.s. your friends are raping people 
p.p.s. you need new friends

#metoo
#thebachelor

doing the right thing is always the right thing. -@garyvee

text:
"slowly things started to fall apart for me"‚Äîactor rosanna arquette speaks with amy goodman and democracy now! about surviving a sexually abusive incident with harvey weinstein in the 1990s and the retaliation that followed. we aired an interview with arquette today from the sundance film festival, which was once a hunting ground for the movie titan weinstein, now accused of sexual assault or misconduct by more than 75 women. arquette also spoke with us about having her phone and computer surveilled by a private israeli spy firm weinstein employed called black cube. arquette is one of the women who speaks out in the new documentary film "untouchable," which just premiered at sundance. hear the full interview on tuesday's show‚Äîfind it at democracynow.org or wherever you get your podcasts. 
#metoo #harveyweinstein #sundance

text:
‚Äúwe wear the mask that grins and lies,
it hides our cheeks and shades our eyes.‚Äî
this debt we pay to human guile;
with torn and bleeding hearts we smile.‚Äù -paul laurence dunbar 
this is just a silly pose ‚Äúselfie‚Äù of a group of friends, right? but let‚Äôs remove the mask for a moment and have a real chat.

last night i had the privilege to host/moderate an event, unpacking the #metoo movement: surviving violence which was a successful, raw, and necessary conversation. @pettydd thank you for organizing and overseeing this spectacular event! 
here are the statistics on sexual abuse: 1 in 4 women will experience sexual violence in their lifetime, and 1 in 6 men.

that means that at least 3 people in this photo are victims of sexual abuse + violence.

those statistics are staggering and show us how the cycle of sexual abuse is perpetuated. all victims of sexual abuse do not become abusers, but there are still just as many that do.  let‚Äôs go a little further.

do you know how many people in this photo would raise their hands if i asked if they have ever been: 1) a victim of sexual harassment in the workplace, 2) at school, or 3) simply done anything physical with someone that they may have ‚Äúconsented‚Äù to but really did not want to?

most likely every single person in this photo, likely with both hands raised! and unfortunately, most likely you.

if you knew this many people around you and perhaps yourself were impacted like this, would you be more compassionate and empathetic of those around you and in public forums such as social media? would you hold space for others and in doing so have more compassion for yourself?

raise your hand below if you have had any of the above experiences. 
if you were at the circles 4 change event last night, please share something new you learned or your biggest takeaway(s). let‚Äôs continue the journey of healing together! 
#healing #metoo #psychology #sexualassault #violence #awareness #growth #movement #community #insight #abuse #circlesforchange #empower
name: MONEY Mindset MITRA

text:
there lots of reasons i wanted to get this, but i chose to justify it today. i haven't been coping well lately and every time i'm super stressed i get inked.
-
i've been out to break a cycle. i always put myself into a path of self destruction because when i was young i was told i would fail. i constantly battle with thoughts that i'm not good enough or worth anyone's time.
-
i was sexually abused by my stepfather from the ages of 10 to 13 and through extensive manipulation starting when i was eight years old, i honestly thought no one would believe me. i still have vivid nightmares where for whatever reason they're together at this time in my life and as i'm screaming at them for what they've done to me they just laugh.
-
i know that a lot of that comes from not telling my mother about the abuse until three years after she left him. she drinks and didn't cope well with it then, and still doesn't. we don't talk about it.
-
the person who saw us out of that hell, and tragically died a year later in a horrific car accident, bought me my first bass. i played it through my fingers bleeding and callouses, and subsequently got introduced to @rageagainthemachine. for a solid year straight i learned and played every song they wrote.
-
my mother after hearing the same bass lines over and over went out and bought a concert dvd, and was pissed when they didn't play "take the power back." yet still i have the image of her, coors light in hand, head banging across the living room screaming the chorus of killing in the name.
-
you reach a certain point of desperation with chronic pain and mental illness that is unrivalled. i wish for a time that was much simpler and i wasn't riddled with such things that make me feel utterly hopeless. it made me wonder what kind of life this is if i don't want to get out of bed at the age of 24 sober anymore than i did at the age of 17 with my nose cavities full of oxycontin.
-
life however is what you make it, and i'm currently in a sea of circumstances for which i can't control and it's extremely uncomfortable. after so much of what has been stolen from me: my sanity at times, my childhood innocence - i have to take the power back.

text:
ughhhh how many times must we go over this? thanks to the #metoo movement, i feel as if men & women are becoming more aware (or at least trying to) when it comes to what‚Äôs appropriate & what‚Äôs harassment. i mean, it‚Äôs really not hard. but sadly this has been going on for centuries. ‚Ä¢

i first encountered this problem while as a stripper. shocking, right? now before anyone jumps to saying ‚Äúwell, you‚Äôre a stripper so you‚Äôre a slut‚Äù or ‚Äúwho cares, you‚Äôre a stripper, that‚Äôs what you‚Äôre there for‚Äù stop ‚úãüèº ‚Ä¢

yes, strippers entice customers by dancing & moving their body. yes, strippers give lap dances. yes, strippers are half if not fully naked. however. that doesn‚Äôt give a man or woman (believe it or not, they can be just as bad if not worse) a right to just walk up to a girl & smack her ass. or reach out & grab her boob as she‚Äôs walking by. even during lap dances, it‚Äôs not ok to just touch. you weren‚Äôt invited to. you can‚Äôt just grope someone because ‚Äúit‚Äôs ok, she‚Äôs a stripper, she‚Äôs half naked, she wants it‚Äù ‚Ä¢

no. it‚Äôs not ok. she doesn‚Äôt want it. thankfully that shit gets shut down right away, thanks to security. ‚Ä¢

sadly this happens daily in the real world. a girl walking down the street in cut off shorts & a crop top gets groped all the time. because she‚Äôs dressed a certain way so ya know. she wants it. i witnessed this first hand walking the las vegas strip last night. fucked up. ‚Ä¢

women & men have the right to dress however, lemme repeat that, however they want without being assaulted or harassed! if someone wants to walk outside rocking some pasties & a tutu, more power to them. clothes do not define you. clothes do not mean she wants it. clothes do not mean she‚Äôs a slut. in fact, nothing means any of that. ‚Ä¢

so ladies, wear your skimpiest skirt, rock your highest heels..wear whatever you want! i have your back ‚úäüèº

text:
cw: trauma.
my bio dad began molesting me when i was five years old. it went on for four years. he was never held accountable. 
an obsessive ex stalked me in my early twenties. he was found guilty and had to pay a fine.
i was raped by a former friends girlfriends brother on the same day my great-grandmother died. i reported it but he was never held accountable because there was insufficient evidence.
i was sexually, verbally, and emotionally abused by a mental health care worker that worked fora place i used to get treatment. she was held accountable and plead guilty. she's still on probation. 
most recently, i was raped by someone who i thought was my friend. i went to the hospital and had a rape kit done but never reported it because i didn't feel like i was mentally stable enough to go through another legal process.

i've been revictimized but don't consider myself to be a victim; i'm a survivor. i have ptsd but despite all this trauma, i'm living. i'm healing. i'm growing. "still, i rise." #metoo #sexualassaultsurvivor #trauma #ptsd

text:
domestic violence laws in california do not protect step parents! help make strangulation a felony! 
we are creating a scenario?! really?
i guess if you are 100% positive you would say some outrageous like this.  it's so typical that a narcissist would turn a violent attack that she did into someone trying to victimize her. this wasn't a custody battle this was a keep a child safe battle and never in court did my husband say he wanted full custody and that only happened temporarily per the request of the child not us. so twisted and really over dramatic. 
this coming from someone that wasn‚Äôt there, never had a conversation in person with us about it and never came to visit to witness use hurt and traumatized. 
what‚Äôs bizarre is that debbie would go to the court with zero evidence and make this statements. at the end of the day it certainly did not help her buddy and only made her look like a liar. 
although she didn‚Äôt need help with that with giving a written declaration and a several different testimonies about what happened. 
i cannot believe we actually thought she was our friend. going through family court was in itself a secondary trauma for all of us. 
it's so sad that so many other families go through this and the judges see it and can't stop the wasting of resources.

text:

text:
a king knows he will genuinely have what he desires for so he never make small plans.

and the scriptures tells us that all things are yours "whether paul, or apollos, or cephas, or the world, or life, or death, or things present, or things to come; all are yours;
1 corinthians 3:22 kjv 
so whatever plans you have to make, for your finances, education, family, ministry or business, never place limitations on yourself. stretch your plans further than your present circumstance could actually reach. that's faith at work.

a king knows he will genuinely have what he desires for so he never make small plans.

and the scriptures tells us that all things are yours "whether paul, or apollos, or cephas, or the world, or life, or death, or things present, or things to come; all are yours;
1 corinthians 3:22 kjv 
so whatever plans you have to make, for your finances, education, family, ministry or business, never place limitations on yourself. stretch your plans further than your present circumstance could actually reach. that's faith at work.

text:
‚Äúyour truth won‚Äôt sound good to every ear,
your truth won‚Äôt fit well in every heart,
your truth won‚Äôt taste sweet on every tongue,
but it‚Äôs still your truth,
and no one can take that away from you.‚Äù
@iambrillyant
.
real talk:
i‚Äôve really struggled to continue putting up my aerial fitness posts. (aerial silks/yoga and pole strength tricks) especially pole tricks. because unfortunately there is a stigma out there. and after some horrible threats, i felt any and all pictures of me would be used against me to hurt me or my family.
.
let me be clear. these are in an aerial fitness studio. an all women studio. a place of fitness, laughing, hard work, flipping upside down and all around on lyra hoops, silks, poles, slings. we all have our reasons for being there. but we all leave with so much body and self confidence. we cheer for each other, we cry with each other and we are a sisterhood. there is nothing sexual about me being there. for me, this studio has been a huge place of healing surrounding myself with powerful and strong af women each week. and nobody on earth gets to tell anybody how they choose to heal after trauma as long as it isn‚Äôt hurting anyone else.
.
this studio was a huge component of my own healing journey. i have so much body confidence and it helped me get ‚Äúback into‚Äù my body after wanting out for months.
.
so this is my truth. i do aerial fitness. and in no way, shape or form does it mean i‚Äôm promiscuous, a bad mom, a horrible human and it will never mean ‚Äúi deserved to be assaulted‚Äù no matter what powerful people may try to twist it. i started this aerial fitness journey after my assault and like i said, it healed my soul and challenged me to get out of my head and body and simply move.
.
i am a fitness woman. i love to challenge myself all.the.time. with new fitness ventures. this is one that took. now 15 months later i still look forward each week to seeing my sister, cheering each other on as we lose skin and get bruises and rip our hands up on these poles, silks, slings and hoops. üôåüèΩüí™üèΩthis is my truth. and i‚Äôve found when you own your truth, people can‚Äôt use it against you because you are living and breathing integrity, honesty and love.
