text_retweet:
a lesson in feminism history:
frida kahlo de rivera born magdalena carmen frida kahlo y calder√≥n; 6 july 1907 ‚Äì 13 july 1954) was a mexican artist who painted many portraits, self-portraits and works inspired by the nature and artifacts of mexico. inspired by the country's popular culture, she employed a na√Øve folk art style to explore questions of identity, postcolonialism, gender, class and race in mexican society. her paintings often had strong autobiographical elements and mixed realism with fantasy. in addition to belonging to the post-revolutionary mexicayotl movement, which sought to define a mexican identity, kahlo has been described as a surrealist or magical realist.
frida smoked, boxed, won tequila challenges against men, and dressed like a man in a family portrait, contrasting to her mother and sisters who wore dresses. she refused to alter her ‚Äòmasculine‚Äô features, including her mono-brow and faint moustache, and actually exaggerated these features in her self portraits. she once wrote in her diary ‚Äúof my face, i like my eyebrows and eyes‚Äù. however she still embraced her femininity, wearing colorful dresses and decorating her hair with braids and flowers.
frida had multiple affairs with both men and women throughout her marriage to diego rivera. she made no apologies or excuses for her sexual choices, a bold act for her time. one of her notable affairs was with entertainer josephine baker, who matched kahlo‚Äôs boldness and creativity.
an artist with physical disabilities and an emotionally challenging life was frida kahlo, why then is she remembered as a feminist icon? frida‚Äôs uniqueness lay in the way she depicted herself in her paintings. she was a brilliant painter of herself and of things that came to her mind, as well as her sources of joys and sorrows, all of this she painted unfettered. her expressions were not molded to fit the societally set standards of what was ‚Äúacceptable‚Äù but she followed her heart and mind. text:
from parasites to nonconsensual biting, oddity and violence abound in ‚Äúyou know you want this,‚Äù the debut short story collection from @kroupenian, who catapulted to fame after writing ‚Äúcat person.‚Äù that story, a relatable study of the pitfalls, manipulations and self-delusions of modern dating, was published in @newyorkermag in december 2017, rapidly went viral, and landed roupenian a seven-figure, two-book deal.
‚Ä¢
in ‚Äúbiter,‚Äù one of the book‚Äôs stories, readers meet ellie, who often bit others in childhood. she knows that won‚Äôt fly in adulthood. when a new, attractive employee, corey, starts working at her office, many women are drawn to him. as is ellie, but her urgings aren‚Äôt romantic. she‚Äôd rather chomp him. to bite or not to bite ‚Äî that is the question permeating the darkly humorous story. in one scene, ellie dons pajamas, pours herself a glass of cabernet and lists reasons not to bite her colleague. the twist ending is strongly reminiscent of #metoo, even though roupenian wrote the story before the movement. (illustration by @thelilynews / istock)

text:
have you all heard of ‚Äòcomfort women‚Äô? before and during ww2, the japanese colonized countries throughout southeast asia forcing over 200,000 women and girls (as young as 13) into sex slavery. many of them were recruited by being told they were going to work in garment factories for the japanese, but instead, would be sent brothels on army bases. there are roughly 26 ‚Äúcomfort women‚Äù still alive today, and they recall daily beatings, brutal rapes and even being forced into using drugs (such as seo-woon chung recalls). they were raped from 8am to 5pm one soldier after the other, no breaks in between by soldierslined up outside their doors. this went on for years. can you even begin to fathom being raped for 8 hrs every single day for years? countless of these women and girls were either killed or committed suicide. those women‚Äôs bodies weren‚Äôt even given proper burials, they were dumped into pens to rot. 
kim book-dong was one of those women. she came from a tight knit family and was manipulated into becoming a ‚Äúcomfort woman‚Äù. she was taken from her home at the age of 14 and returned when she was 21. for years, she never spoke about the horrors she endured. it wasn‚Äôt until she was 60 that she decided to tell the world her story. since then, she has been an outspoken advocate for ‚Äúcomfort women‚Äù throughout asia. she passed away today at the age of 92.

now i see men getting irritated that women are becoming more and more vocal about sexual abuse and unfair treatment. for years, we (women) didn‚Äôt have a voice, treated as less than animals, with absolutely no regard for our humanity. and to think, there are men who are pissed off at the #metoo movement. this is the definition of #toxicmasculinity : lack of compassion and denial for human suffering. this is why women are pissed the tf off. there is so much shame and secrecy surrounding sexual abuse (of women) and domestic abuse. however more of us are awakening to courage and demanding our voices be heard. 
the japanese gov‚Äôt has yet to issue a formal apology for the (mis)treatment of these women and the ongoing trauma they and their families continue to endure. 
i hope that ms. kim is finally resting peacefully.

text:
good morning! its tuesday so ya know that means... #textyourfriendtuesday !!! if you haven't been following my personal account then you might be asking yourself what the heck is that?! share and let's change the world! this will be a 2 part post... post1

a while back i thought to myself, we have #tacotuesday, mcm, wcw, tbt, and tons of other weekly hashtags that everyone loves to participate in, so why not have one that can make a difference in our lives?! i feel like we need to raise awareness about mental health and suicide. text your friend tuesday is a weekly reminder to check on a friend. maybe someone you havent talked to in a while, someone you noticed hasn't been posting as much as they usually do, or posting things that are unusual for them. 
for example, there were many times that i have thought to myself..."hmm "susan" seems a little down, i should check on her invite her over" or "that's unusual to post, she's usually so positive and strong, i should check in on her and let her know i'm here for her" or "wow, i havent heard from "susan" in a while i wonder how she is" but it always seems like its too early or late in the day to check in on someone and midday i get so busy that i forget and the cycle will start all over again and who knows when i will check in on them...meanwhile i'm posting my taco tuesday post or throwback pictures! so now i use textyourfriendtuesday to remind myself to check on people and maybe go grab tacos tuesday!

i've also been on the other side, the friend needing a text or a call. many times i remember sitting in my car or even sitting on my bathroom floor hiding from the world, feeling alone, crying my eyes out, and just wondering if this is what life was all about. then i would get a random text or a call from a friend or family member, and boy did that help! they had no idea what i was feeling at that moment and how much i needed that check in. i'll get into more of my story later, but you get the point. a simple hey can really change someone's day, even their life!!

text:
continued....part2 #textyourfriendtuesday 
mental health comes in many forms and it doesnt matter your age, sex, religion, race... and theres no simple cure! i can't tell you how many times i've heard that i need to just think happy thoughts or pray or find the positive. those are great tools and i do them daily, but it's not as simple as it sounds and just doing one of those things will not cure mental health. i never want my kids, my family, my friends, or anyone to feel how i have felt.

this page will be about spreading mental health awareness, positivity, uplifting each other, my story and how i've overcome so much (i have a diagnosed chronic autoimmune disorder, myasthenia gravis, anxiety, ptsd) and most importantly a weekly reminder to check on your loved ones!! share and let's change the world!!!

.

text:
people who are posting these kind of posts need to understand that empowerment is not restricted to one particular way in which it could be achieved. 
joining the army is one strong way to prove that we‚Äôre equally responsible for our respective countries. 
but if you think empowerment happens only in that way, oh boy! you‚Äôre wrong, naive and stupid. 
there are many teachers, students, speakers, authors, women empowerment committees and communities who are working really hard in teaching the society that women have a voice and it has to be heard. that‚Äôs not an option, and it is their right. 
what makes you think that these women in the post are different? they are both wanting the change but in different ways. 
speaking for the speakers in the post( to the top right and bottom right), they have always mentioned about the change they wish to see, they‚Äôve raised their voices for the incidents they had seen and god forbid had experienced. 
why is it that their point of view is shit? 
is it because of your ‚Äúmale ego‚Äù that doesn‚Äôt wanna accept, that there are few men who indeed are the root cause of these topics? or is it because they‚Äôve given courage to other young women to accept their flaws,speak about the mistakes that had been happening with them and to voice their opinions in various situations? 
to burst your bubble, the speakers in the post were never talking about the entire gender or the community. they‚Äôve always mentioned about the corrupt thoughts of society and the foul behaviour of certain people. 
there are various ways to achieve the goal of equal rights, in that process, everyone‚Äôs contribution is considered. no one here is gonna call anyone‚Äôs effort ‚Äúshit‚Äù just cause it doesn‚Äôt go with your perception of equality. 
these are the women who are speaking about ‚Äútaboo‚Äù topics, these are the women who are giving comfort to millions of people, these are the women who are making the world less uncomfortable for us. 
you should be proud to have been called millennials and having to share an opportunity to encourage and support such great intentions and work. 
as a fellow speaker, writer and human being, it is absurd to watch people write ‚Äúshit‚Äù on internet.
